pathophysiology and clinical trials. Key identified issues include better understanding of the role of pulmonary venous versus arteriolar remodelling, multidimensional phenotyping to recognize patient subgroups positioned to respond to different therapies, and conduct of rigorous pre-clinical studies combining small and large animal models. Advancements in these areas are expected to better inform the design of clinical trials and extend treatment options beyond those effective in pulmonary arterial hypertension. Enrichment strategies, endpoint assessments, and thorough haemodynamic studies, both at rest and during exercise, are proposed to play primary roles to optimize early-stage development of candidate therapies for PH-LHF. ","{14514,14515,14516,14517,14518,14519,14520,14521,14522,14523,14524,14525,14526,14527,14528,14529,14530,14531,14532,14533,14534,14535,14536,14537,14538,14539,14540,14541,14542,14543,14544,14545,14546,14547,14548,14549,14550,14551,14552,14553,14554,14555,14556,14557,14558,14559,14560,14561,14562,14563,14564,14565,14566,14567,14568,14569,14570,14571,14572,14573,14574,14575,14576,14577,14578,14579,14580,14581,14582,14583,14584,14585,14586,14587,14588,14589,14590,14591,14592,14593,14594,14595,14596,14597,14598,14599,14600,14601,14602,14603,14604,14605,14606,14607,14608,14609,14610,14611,14612,14613,14614,14615,14616,14617,14618,14619,14620,14621,14622}","476","1123","{3673,3674,3675,3676,3677,3678,3679,3680,3681,3682}","5"
