ttps://openalex.org/W2077922474,https://openalex.org/W2088894776,https://openalex.org/W2097259163,https://openalex.org/W2097690118,https://openalex.org/W2097990780,https://openalex.org/W2098613050,https://openalex.org/W2101679999,https://openalex.org/W2102322990,https://openalex.org/W2148857656,https://openalex.org/W2153969860,https://openalex.org/W2155184340,https://openalex.org/W2160375286,https://openalex.org/W2162058407,https://openalex.org/W2167279371,https://openalex.org/W2171520735,https://openalex.org/W2234931000,https://openalex.org/W2254906934,https://openalex.org/W2265915648,https://openalex.org/W2334665931,https://openalex.org/W2598011934,https://openalex.org/W2625684162,https://openalex.org/W2697742764,https://openalex.org/W2782256676,https://openalex.org/W2796527262,https://openalex.org/W2883522227,https://openalex.org/W2899443670,https://openalex.org/W2924530200,https://openalex.org/W2952574460,https://openalex.org/W2998416656,https://openalex.org/W2998967758,https://openalex.org/W3006010054,https://openalex.org/W3010402261,https://openalex.org/W3011241500,https://openalex.org/W3047752960,https://openalex.org/W3082726941,https://openalex.org/W3085554512,https://openalex.org/W4206043315,https://openalex.org/W4220967167,https://openalex.org/W4302362773,https://openalex.org/W4309078436,https://openalex.org/W4377246555,https://openalex.org/W4383818900,https://openalex.org/W4386397267,https://openalex.org/W4386399714,https://openalex.org/W4388021187,https://openalex.org/W4389160748}","{https://openalex.org/W2314825334,https://openalex.org/W2410947740,https://openalex.org/W2891404117,https://openalex.org/W2008713788,https://openalex.org/W2472294291,https://openalex.org/W2417959622,https://openalex.org/W2079598623,https://openalex.org/W2056444349,https://openalex.org/W4206078893,https://openalex.org/W2095987251}","Summary Glycolysis has traditionally been thought to take place in the cytosol but we observed the enrichment of glycolytic enzymes in propagating waves of the cell cortex in human epithelial cells. These waves reflect excitable Ras/PI3K signal transduction and F-actin/actomyosin networks that drive cellular protrusions, suggesting that localized glycolysis at the cortex provides ATP for cell morphological events such as migration, phagocytosis, and cytokinesis. Perturbations that altered cortical waves caused corresponding changes in enzyme localization and ATP production whereas synthetic recruitment of glycolytic enzymes to the cell cortex enhanced cell spreading and motility. Interestingly, the cortical waves and ATP levels were positively correlated with the metastatic potential of cancer cells. The coordinated signal transduction, cytoskeletal, and glycolytic waves in cancer cells may explain their increased motility and their greater reliance on glycolysis, often referred to as the Warburg effect. ","{19351,19352,19353,19354,19355,19356,15482}","807","469",NULL,"5"
